{"title_page": "Atalanta", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek mythological character}}\n{{about|the Greek mythological character}}\n{{distinguish|Atlanta}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Atalanta Vatican Inv2784.jpg|thumb|383x383px|The \"Barberini Atalanta\",<ref>In the opinion of Lempriere's Classical Dictionary, \"the finest representation of Atalanta\"</ref> formerly in the [[Barberini Palace]], Rome, now in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]], inv. 2784. Either Greek original, 1st century BC or Roman copy, 2nd century AD]]\n\n'''Atalanta''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u00e6|t|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u00e6|n|t|\u0259}}; {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f08\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7}} ''Atalant\u0113'') is a character in [[Greek mythology]], a virgin huntress, unwilling to marry, and loved by the hero [[Meleager]].\n\nAccording to the [[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|''Bibliotheca'' of ''pseudo-Apollodorus'']], Atalanta was the daughter of [[Iasus]], son of [[Lycurgus of Arcadia|Lycurgus]], and [[Clymene (mythology)|Clymene]], daughter of [[Minyas (mythology)|Minyas]].<ref>Pseudo-[[Apollodorus of Athens|Apollodorus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.9.2 3.9.2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152754/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.9.2 |date=2015-09-24 }}.</ref> She is also mentioned as the daughter of Mainalos or [[Schoeneus]] (according to [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]]), of a [[Boeotia]]n (according to [[Hesiod]]), or of an [[Arcadia]]n princess (according to the ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]''). The ''Bibliotheca'' is the only source which gives an account of Atalanta's birth and upbringing. Prince [[Iasus]] wanted a son; when Atalanta was born, he left her on a mountaintop to die. Some stories say that a she-[[Bears in antiquity|bear]] suckled and cared for Atalanta until hunters found and raised her, and she learned to fight and hunt as a bear would. She was later reunited with her father.\n\nHaving grown up in the wilderness, Atalanta became a fierce hunter and was always happy. She took an oath of [[virginity]] to the goddess [[Artemis]], and slew two centaurs, [[Hylaeus and Rhoecus]], who attempted to rape her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoi.com/Heroine/Atalanta.html|title=ATALANTA (Atalante) - Arcadian Heroine of Greek Mythology|website=www.theoi.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930094907/http://www.theoi.com/Heroine/Atalanta.html|archivedate=2012-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thanasis.com/store/atalanta.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823054804/http://www.thanasis.com/store/atalanta.htm |archivedate=2012-08-23 }}</ref>\n\n==Calydonian Boar Hunt==\n[[File:Peter Paul Rubens (and workshop) Meleager and Atalante.jpg|thumb|left|278x278px|Meleager, assisted by [[Cupid]], presents Atalanta with the head of the Calydonian Boar. Oil on panel, studio of [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]], Rothschild collection, Ch\u00e2teau de Ferri\u00e8res. Another large version by Rubens c.1635 is at the Alte Pinakothek, Munich, and a smaller version at the Walker Art Gallery, Liverpool]]\n\nWhen Artemis was forgotten at a sacrifice by [[Oineus|King Oineus]], she was angered and sent the [[Calydonian Boar]], a [[wild boar]] that ravaged the land, men, and cattle and prevented crops from being sown. Atalanta joined [[Meleager]] and many other famous heroes on a hunt for the boar. Many of the men were angry that a woman was joining them, but Meleager, though married, lusted for Atalanta, and so he persuaded them to include her. Several of the men were killed before Atalanta became the first to hit the boar and draw blood. After Meleager finally killed the boar with his spear, he awarded the hide to Atalanta. This act of Meleager\u2019s generosity caused a set of events that led to his death.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOgWfjNIxoMC&lpg=PP1&ots=Njj29ss-a-&dq=Encyclopedia%20of%20Greek%20and%20roman%20mythology%20cite&lr&hl=uk&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=Encyclopedia%20of%20Greek%20and%20roman%20mythology%20cite&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Greek and Roman Mythology|last=Roman|first=Luke|last2=Roman|first2=Monica|date=2010|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=|isbn=9781438126395|location=|pages=88|language=en}}</ref> Meleager's uncles, Plexippus and Toxeus, were angry and tried to take the skin from her. In revenge, Meleager killed his uncles. Wild with grief, Meleager's mother [[Althaea (mythology)|Althaea]] threw a charmed log on the fire, which consumed Meleager's life as it burned.\n\n== Footrace ==\n[[File:Hip\u00f3menes y Atalanta (Reni).jpg|thumb|350px|Guido Reni \u2013 ''[[Atalanta and Hippomenes]]'' \u2013 WGA19271]]\nAfter the Calydonian boar hunt, Atalanta was rediscovered by her father. He wanted her to be married, but Atalanta, uninterested in marriage, agreed to marry only if her suitors could outrun her in a [[footrace]]. Those who lost would be killed. King Oeneus agreed, and many young men died in the attempt until [[Hippomenes]], a grandson of [[Poseidon]], came along.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hippomenes asked the goddess [[Aphrodite]] for help, and she gave him three golden apples in order to slow Atalanta down. The apples were irresistible, so every time Atalanta got ahead of Hippomenes, he rolled an apple ahead of her, and she would run after it. In this way, Hippomenes won the footrace and came to marry Atalanta. In some versions, Atalanta loved Hippomenes and hoped he would win.<ref name=\":0\" /> Eventually they had a son [[Parthenopeus|Parthenopaios]], who was one of the [[Seven against Thebes]]. [[Zeus]] \u2013 or his mother, [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]] \u2013 turned Atalanta and Hippomenes into lions after they had sex together in one of his temples. Other accounts say that Aphrodite changed them into lions because they did not give her proper honor. The belief at the time was that lions could not mate with their own species, only with leopards; thus Atalanta and Hippomenes would never be able to remain with one another.\n\n== The ''Argo'' ==\n\nIn many versions of the quest for the [[Golden Fleece]], such as that published by [[Robert Graves]] in 1944, Atalanta sailed with the [[Argonauts]] as the only woman among them. She jumped aboard the ship soon after the expedition set out, invoking the protection of Artemis, to whom she was a virgin priestess. She was following Meleager, who had put away his young wife for Atalanta's sake. Atalanta returned his love but was prevented by an oracle from consummating their union, being warned that losing her virginity would prove disastrous for her. A disappointed Meleager joined the ''Argo'', but Atalanta would not let him out of her sight. She plays a major part in various adventures of Jason's crew, suffered injury in a battle at [[Colchis]], and was healed by [[Medea]]. [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], on the other hand, claims [[Jason]] would not allow a woman on the ship because she would cause strife on the otherwise all-male expedition (Argonautica 1.769\u201373).\n\n==Wrestling==\n\n[[File:Atalanta Peleus Staatliche Antikensammlungen 596.jpg|thumb|right|280px|[[Peleus]] and Atalanta wrestling, black-figured [[hydria]], c. 550 BC, [[Staatliche Antikensammlungen]] (Inv. 596).]]\nThe ''Bibliotheca'' also says she wrestled and defeated [[Peleus]] at the funeral games for [[Pelias]]. The subject is popular in ancient Greek vase painting.\n\n==Cultural depictions==\n[[File:Nicolas Colombel 002.jpg|thumb|225x225px|The Race between Atalanta and [[Hippomenes]], by [[Nicolas Colombel]] (1644\u20131717), [[Liechtenstein Museum]], Vienna. Atalanta is slowed as she picks up the golden apples rolled down by her rival|left]]\n*In Ovid's Metamorphosis Aphrodite tells the story of the footrace, and what follows, including a mysterious prophecy which in this version scared Atalanta away from marriage.\n*Founded in 1907 in [[Bergamo]] by local \"liceo classico\" (high school) students, football club [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta Bergamasca Calcio]] gets its name from the Greek deity. The club is for this reason also nicknamed \"La Dea\" (the Goddess) by its supporters.\n* The German mythologist, epigramist, composer, physician and counsellor to [[Rudolf II]], [[Michael Maier]] published ''[[Atalanta Fugiens]]'' in 1617, an early work of mixed media which included an epigrammatic verse on the Greek myth, along with 50 emblematic images and music [[fugue]]s relating to Atalanta's flight.\n* [[George Frederick Handel|Handel]] wrote a 1736 opera about the character, ''[[Atalanta (opera)|Atalanta]]''. \n* In the 20th century, [[Robert Ashley]] also wrote an opera, ''Atalanta (Acts of God)'', with loose allegorical connections to the myth. \n* Other works based on the myth include a play by [[Algernon Charles Swinburne]], ''Atalanta in Calydon'', written (in the style of [[Greek tragedy]]) in 1865. \n* Comic books have also used versions of her story, including ''Hercules: the Thracian Wars'', and ''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.\n* Versions of the story of Atalanta appear in the television series ''[[Atlantis (TV series)|Atlantis]]'' produced by BBC, ''[[Hercules: The Legendary Journeys]]'', the Hallmark mini-series of ''Jason and the Argonauts'', and ''[[Free to Be... You and Me]]'' (featuring the footrace only, Hippomenes renamed Young John, no death penalty for the losers, no golden apples, a tie, and a mutual decision that both would explore the world leaving open the question of marriage). \n* Video game appearances include the ''[[Golden Sun]]'' series, ''[[Herc's Adventures]]'', an expansion of ''[[Zeus: Master of Olympus]]'', ''[[Rise of the Argonauts]]'', and ''[[Age of Mythology]]''.\n* Atalanta also appears in the 2014 film ''[[Hercules (2014 film)|Hercules]]'', where she is depicted as an Amazonian archer, and member of Hercules' traveling band of mercenaries.\n* Atalanta appears in the light novel series ''[[Fate/Apocrypha]]'' (2012\u20132014) as the Archer of Red, and the mobile game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]''.\n* In the late 1920s, [[Studebaker]] adopted Atalanta as a symbolic [[hood ornament]] for its cars.<ref>[http://www.stude100.com/stu/Pg3/pg3.php The Golden Age] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010638/http://www.stude100.com/stu/Pg3/pg3.php |date=2015-05-11 }} at Studebaker 100 historical website</ref>\n* There have been several British car manufacturing companies that used the name ''Atalanta'', most notably Atalanta Motors Ltd. of Staines Middlesex UK, in operation 1937-39.<ref>Wikipedia entry for Atalanta_(1937_automobile)[[Atalanta (1937 automobile)]]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Grant |first1=Gregor |title=British Sports Cars |date=1948 |publisher=Floyd Clymer |location=Los Angeles |pages=37-43 |edition=1st }}</ref>\n* Atalanta is the subject of the song ''Atalanta's Hand'' by Emilia Dahlin on her album Stealing Glimpses.\n*Elizabeth Tammi's ''Outrun the Wind'' brings a unique twist to the story of Atalanta.\n*The Atalanta Sandals are a piece of Legendary Armor that can be equipped in [[Assassin's Creed Odyssey]] and part of the Greek Heroes Armor Set, which also includes the Perseus Helmet, Jason's Golden Fleece, Hippolyta's Belt and the Bracers of Theseus. All of which can be acquired by defeating specific mercenaries.\n* An [[audiobook]] retelling of the story for children, ''Diana and the Golden Apples'', was narrated by [[Art Gilmore]] with an orchestral backing of [[Prokofiev]]'s [[Lieutenant Kij\u00e9 (Prokofiev)|Lieutenant Kije]], and released by [[Capitol Records]] in the 1950s.<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/The-Continental-Symphony-Orchestra-Art-Gilmore-Diana-And-The-Golden-Apples/master/1438764 Discogs - Diana and the Golden Apples]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=30389&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=14905719|title=Diana and the golden apples|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]}}</ref> An accompanying animated short was also produced by [[Mel-O-Toons]].\n* ''Atalanta and the Arcadian Beast'' is a 2003 novel by [[Robert J. Harris (writer)|Robert J. Harris]] and [[Jane Yolen]], part of the ''Young Heroe'' series.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\nFile:Richard Wilson - Meleager and Atalanta - Google Art Project.jpg|Richard Wilson - Meleager and Atalanta (circa 1770)\nFile:Meleager-B\u00e9ierkapp--w.jpg|L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Meleager B\u00e9ierkapp\nFile:Jan Wildens - Landscape with Hunt of Meleager and Atalanta.jpg|Landscape with Hunt of Meleager and Atalanta by Jan Wildens (17th century) at Geschonken aan het museum door Artibus Patriae, Antwerpen, 1938.\nFile:Jacob Jordaens - Meleager en Atalanta.JPG|Meleager and Atalanta by Jacob Jordaens (circa 1618) at the Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp, Belgium\nFile:Meleager presents the Boar's head to Atalanta.jpg|Meleager presents the Boar's head to Atalanta. From Neuer\u00f6ffneter Musen-Tempel by Bernard Picart, 1733 (University of Heidelberg)\nFile:Atalanta and Meleager MET DP261342.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager by Peter Paul Rubens (ca. 1616) at Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York City\nFile:Giulio Romano - Meleager et Atalanta.jpg|\"Meleager et Atalanta\", from a drawing by [[Giulio Romano]], engraved by Fran\u00e7ois Louis Lonsing. Atalanta is the woman on the far left with the bow; Meleager is just right of her, with the boar spear sticking into the Calydonian Boar. (1773)\nFile:Jan Fyt and Pieter Thijs - Atalanta and Meleager Hunt the Calydonian Boar.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager Hunt the Calydonian Boar by Jan Fyt and Pieter Thijs (1648) at Ringling Museum of Art, Sarasota, Florida\nFile:Francesco Mosca, called Il Moschino - Atalanta and Meleager with the Calydonian Boar, ca. 1564-1565 - Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art - DSC08046.JPG|Atalanta and Meleager with the Calydonian Boar by Francesco Mosca, called Il Moschino (ca. 1564-1565).  Exhibit in the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri\nFile:M. Maurice Stora - Atalanta and Meleager Present the Head of the Caledonian Boar at the Temple of Artemis - Google Art Project.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager Present the Head of the Caledonian Boar at the Temple of Artemis by M. Maurice Stora (1530 - 1535) at Toledo Museum of Art, Toledo, Ohio\nFile:Meleager en Atalanta Rijksmuseum SK-A-4121.jpeg|Meleager en Atalanta (between 1675 and 1699) at Rijksmuseum Amsterdam\nFile:Jacob Jordaens - Meleager and Atalanta, 1620-1650.jpg|Meleager and Atalante by Jacob Jordaens (1620-1650) at Museo Nacional del Prado, Madrid, Spain\nFile:Paolo Veronese (c\u00edrculo) - Atalanta e Hipomenes disputando a corrida.JPG|English:  by Circle of Paolo Veronese (f1550-1600) at National Museum of Ancient Art, Lisbon, Portugal\nFile:No\u00ebl Hall\u00e9 - The Race between Hippomenes and Atalanta - WGA11034.jpg|The Race between Hippomenes and Atalanta by No\u00ebl Hall\u00e9 (1762-1765) at Louvre Museum, Paris\nFile:Herp Atalanta and Hippomenes.jpg|Atalanta and Hippomenes by Willem van Herp (circa 1650) at National Museum in Warsaw\nFile:Les Metamorphoses d'Ovide - Atalanta and Hippomenes.jpg|Engraving by Magdalena van de Passe from book Les Metamorphoses d'Ovide, En Latin Et Fran\u00e7ois: Divis\u00e9es En XV. Livres, page 335. Published 1677.\nFile:Johann Heinrich Sch\u00f6nfeld - Atalanta and Hippomenes - WGA21056.jpg|Atalanta and Hippomenes by Johann Heinrich Sch\u00f6nfeld (1650-1660) at Brukenthal National Museum, Sibiu, Romania\nFile:Francis Derwent Wood, Atalanta Preparing for the Race, front 2, Chelsea Embankment at Albert Bridge, London (3381529189).jpg\nFile:Francis Derwent Wood - Atalanta.jpg\nFile:Atalanta Lepautre Louvre MR1804.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Apollodorus, ''Bibliotheca'' 3. 9. 2 for Atalanta and 1.8.3 for the Boar Hunt\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Atalanta}}\n* [http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/picture-of-month/displaypicture.asp?venue=2&id=6 Rubens's \"Atalanta and Meleager\"] in the [http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/ladylever/ Lady Lever Art Gallery]\n*{{ws|[[s:Landon in The Literary Gazette 1823/Atalanta|Atalanta, represented as a Huntress with her bow]]}} One of the Medallion Wafer poems of [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]] in the Literary Gazette, 1823.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Argonauts]]\n[[Category:Fictional feral children]]\n[[Category:Metamorphoses into animals in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological Greek archers]]\n[[Category:Women in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Princesses in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Arcadian mythology]]\n[[Category:Boeotian mythology]]\n[[Category:Family of Athamas]]\n[[Category:Fictional hunters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek mythological character}}\n{{about|the Greek mythological character}}\n{{distinguish|Atlanta}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2016}}\n[[File:Atalanta Vatican Inv2784.jpg|thumb|383x383px|The \"Barberini Atalanta\",<ref>In the opinion of Lempriere's Classical Dictionary, \"the finest representation of Atalanta\"</ref> formerly in the [[Barberini Palace]], Rome, now in the [[Vatican City|Vatican]], inv. 2784. Either Greek original, 1st century BC or Roman copy, 2nd century AD]]\n\n'''Atalanta''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u00e6|t|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u00e6|n|t|\u0259}}; {{lang-grc-gre|\u1f08\u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7}} ''Atalant\u0113'') is a character in [[Greek mythology]], a virgin huntress, unwilling to marry, and loved by the hero [[Meleager]].\n\nAccording to the ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]'' of ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|pseudo-Apollodorus]]'', Atalanta was the daughter of [[Iasus]], son of [[Lycurgus of Arcadia|Lycurgus]], and [[Clymene (mythology)|Clymene]], daughter of [[Minyas (mythology)|Minyas]].<ref>Pseudo-[[Apollodorus of Athens|Apollodorus]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.9.2 3.9.2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152754/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.9.2 |date=2015-09-24 }}.</ref> She is also mentioned as the daughter of Mainalos or [[Schoeneus]] (according to [[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]]), of a [[Boeotia]]n (according to [[Hesiod]]), or of an [[Arcadia]]n princess (according to the ''[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Bibliotheca]]''). The ''Bibliotheca'' is the only source which gives an account of Atalanta's birth and upbringing. Prince [[Iasus]] wanted a son; when Atalanta was born, he left her on a mountaintop to die. Some stories say that a she-[[Bears in antiquity|bear]] suckled and cared for Atalanta until hunters found and raised her, and she learned to fight and hunt as a bear would. She was later reunited with her father.\n\nHaving grown up in the wilderness, Atalanta became a fierce hunter and was always happy. She took an oath of [[virginity]] to the goddess [[Artemis]], and slew two centaurs, [[Hylaeus and Rhoecus]], who attempted to rape her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theoi.com/Heroine/Atalanta.html|title=ATALANTA (Atalante) - Arcadian Heroine of Greek Mythology|website=www.theoi.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930094907/http://www.theoi.com/Heroine/Atalanta.html|archivedate=2012-09-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thanasis.com/store/atalanta.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120823054804/http://www.thanasis.com/store/atalanta.htm |archivedate=2012-08-23 }}</ref>\n\n==Calydonian Boar Hunt==\n[[File:Peter Paul Rubens (and workshop) Meleager and Atalante.jpg|thumb|left|278x278px|Meleager, assisted by [[Cupid]], presents Atalanta with the head of the Calydonian Boar. Oil on panel, studio of [[Peter Paul Rubens|Rubens]], Rothschild collection, Ch\u00e2teau de Ferri\u00e8res. Another large version by Rubens c.1635 is at the Alte Pinakothek, Munich, and a smaller version at the Walker Art Gallery, Liverpool]]\n\nWhen Artemis was forgotten at a sacrifice by [[Oineus|King Oineus]], she was angered and sent the [[Calydonian Boar]], a [[wild boar]] that ravaged the land, men, and cattle and prevented crops from being sown. Atalanta joined [[Meleager]] and many other famous heroes on a hunt for the boar. Many of the men were angry that a woman was joining them, but Meleager, though married, lusted for Atalanta, and so he persuaded them to include her. Several of the men were killed before Atalanta became the first to hit the boar and draw blood. After Meleager finally killed the boar with his spear, he awarded the hide to Atalanta. This act of Meleager\u2019s generosity caused a set of events that led to his death.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tOgWfjNIxoMC&lpg=PP1&ots=Njj29ss-a-&dq=Encyclopedia%20of%20Greek%20and%20roman%20mythology%20cite&lr&hl=uk&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q=Encyclopedia%20of%20Greek%20and%20roman%20mythology%20cite&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Greek and Roman Mythology|last=Roman|first=Luke|last2=Roman|first2=Monica|date=2010|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=|isbn=9781438126395|location=|pages=88|language=en}}</ref> Meleager's uncles, Plexippus and Toxeus, were angry and tried to take the skin from her. In revenge, Meleager killed his uncles. Wild with grief, Meleager's mother [[Althaea (mythology)|Althaea]] threw a charmed log on the fire, which consumed Meleager's life as it burned.\n\n== Footrace ==\n[[File:Hip\u00f3menes y Atalanta (Reni).jpg|thumb|350px|Guido Reni \u2013 ''[[Atalanta and Hippomenes]]'' \u2013 WGA19271]]\nAfter the Calydonian boar hunt, Atalanta was rediscovered by her father. He wanted her to be married, but Atalanta, uninterested in marriage, agreed to marry only if her suitors could outrun her in a [[footrace]]. Those who lost would be killed. King Oeneus agreed, and many young men died in the attempt until [[Hippomenes]], a grandson of [[Poseidon]], came along.<ref name=\":0\" /> Hippomenes asked the goddess [[Aphrodite]] for help, and she gave him three golden apples in order to slow Atalanta down. The apples were irresistible, so every time Atalanta got ahead of Hippomenes, he rolled an apple ahead of her, and she would run after it. In this way, Hippomenes won the footrace and came to marry Atalanta. In some versions, Atalanta loved Hippomenes and hoped he would win.<ref name=\":0\" /> Eventually they had a son [[Parthenopeus|Parthenopaios]], who was one of the [[Seven against Thebes]]. [[Zeus]] \u2013 or his mother, [[Rhea (mythology)|Rhea]] \u2013 turned Atalanta and Hippomenes into lions after they had sex together in one of his temples. Other accounts say that Aphrodite changed them into lions because they did not give her proper honor. The belief at the time was that lions could not mate with their own species, only with leopards; thus Atalanta and Hippomenes would never be able to remain with one another.\n\n== The ''Argo'' ==\n\nIn many versions of the quest for the [[Golden Fleece]], such as that published by [[Robert Graves]] in 1944, Atalanta sailed with the [[Argonauts]] as the only woman among them. She jumped aboard the ship soon after the expedition set out, invoking the protection of Artemis, to whom she was a virgin priestess. She was following Meleager, who had put away his young wife for Atalanta's sake. Atalanta returned his love but was prevented by an oracle from consummating their union, being warned that losing her virginity would prove disastrous for her. A disappointed Meleager joined the ''Argo'', but Atalanta would not let him out of her sight. She plays a major part in various adventures of Jason's crew, suffered injury in a battle at [[Colchis]], and was healed by [[Medea]]. [[Apollonius of Rhodes]], on the other hand, claims [[Jason]] would not allow a woman on the ship because she would cause strife on the otherwise all-male expedition (Argonautica 1.769\u201373).\n\n==Wrestling==\n\n[[File:Atalanta Peleus Staatliche Antikensammlungen 596.jpg|thumb|right|280px|[[Peleus]] and Atalanta wrestling, black-figured [[hydria]], c. 550 BC, [[Staatliche Antikensammlungen]] (Inv. 596).]]\nThe ''Bibliotheca'' also says she wrestled and defeated [[Peleus]] at the funeral games for [[Pelias]]. The subject is popular in ancient Greek vase painting.\n\n==Cultural depictions==\n[[File:Nicolas Colombel 002.jpg|thumb|225x225px|The Race between Atalanta and [[Hippomenes]], by [[Nicolas Colombel]] (1644\u20131717), [[Liechtenstein Museum]], Vienna. Atalanta is slowed as she picks up the golden apples rolled down by her rival|left]]\n*In Ovid's Metamorphosis Aphrodite tells the story of the footrace, and what follows, including a mysterious prophecy which in this version scared Atalanta away from marriage.\n*Founded in 1907 in [[Bergamo]] by local \"liceo classico\" (high school) students, football club [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta Bergamasca Calcio]] gets its name from the Greek deity. The club is for this reason also nicknamed \"La Dea\" (the Goddess) by its supporters.\n* The German mythologist, epigramist, composer, physician and counsellor to [[Rudolf II]], [[Michael Maier]] published ''[[Atalanta Fugiens]]'' in 1617, an early work of mixed media which included an epigrammatic verse on the Greek myth, along with 50 emblematic images and music [[fugue]]s relating to Atalanta's flight.\n* [[George Frederick Handel|Handel]] wrote a 1736 opera about the character, ''[[Atalanta (opera)|Atalanta]]''. \n* In the 20th century, [[Robert Ashley]] also wrote an opera, ''Atalanta (Acts of God)'', with loose allegorical connections to the myth. \n* Other works based on the myth include a play by [[Algernon Charles Swinburne]], ''Atalanta in Calydon'', written (in the style of [[Greek tragedy]]) in 1865. \n* Comic books have also used versions of her story, including ''Hercules: the Thracian Wars'', and ''[[The Incredible Hulk (comic book)|The Incredible Hulk]]''.\n* Versions of the story of Atalanta appear in the television series ''[[Atlantis (TV series)|Atlantis]]'' produced by BBC, ''[[Hercules: The Legendary Journeys]]'', the Hallmark mini-series of ''Jason and the Argonauts'', and ''[[Free to Be... You and Me]]'' (featuring the footrace only, Hippomenes renamed Young John, no death penalty for the losers, no golden apples, a tie, and a mutual decision that both would explore the world leaving open the question of marriage). \n* Video game appearances include the ''[[Golden Sun]]'' series, ''[[Herc's Adventures]]'', an expansion of ''[[Zeus: Master of Olympus]]'', ''[[Rise of the Argonauts]]'', and ''[[Age of Mythology]]''.\n* Atalanta also appears in the 2014 film ''[[Hercules (2014 film)|Hercules]]'', where she is depicted as an Amazonian archer, and member of Hercules' traveling band of mercenaries.\n* Atalanta appears in the light novel series ''[[Fate/Apocrypha]]'' (2012\u20132014) as the Archer of Red, and the mobile game ''[[Fate/Grand Order]]''.\n* In the late 1920s, [[Studebaker]] adopted Atalanta as a symbolic [[hood ornament]] for its cars.<ref>[http://www.stude100.com/stu/Pg3/pg3.php The Golden Age] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150511010638/http://www.stude100.com/stu/Pg3/pg3.php |date=2015-05-11 }} at Studebaker 100 historical website</ref>\n* There have been several British car manufacturing companies that used the name ''Atalanta'', most notably Atalanta Motors Ltd. of Staines Middlesex UK, in operation 1937-39.<ref>Wikipedia entry for Atalanta_(1937_automobile)[[Atalanta (1937 automobile)]]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Grant |first1=Gregor |title=British Sports Cars |date=1948 |publisher=Floyd Clymer |location=Los Angeles |pages=37-43 |edition=1st }}</ref>\n* Atalanta is the subject of the song ''Atalanta's Hand'' by Emilia Dahlin on her album Stealing Glimpses.\n*Elizabeth Tammi's ''Outrun the Wind'' brings a unique twist to the story of Atalanta.\n*The Atalanta Sandals are a piece of Legendary Armor that can be equipped in [[Assassin's Creed Odyssey]] and part of the Greek Heroes Armor Set, which also includes the Perseus Helmet, Jason's Golden Fleece, Hippolyta's Belt and the Bracers of Theseus. All of which can be acquired by defeating specific mercenaries.\n* An [[audiobook]] retelling of the story for children, ''Diana and the Golden Apples'', was narrated by [[Art Gilmore]] with an orchestral backing of [[Prokofiev]]'s [[Lieutenant Kij\u00e9 (Prokofiev)|Lieutenant Kije]], and released by [[Capitol Records]] in the 1950s.<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/The-Continental-Symphony-Orchestra-Art-Gilmore-Diana-And-The-Golden-Apples/master/1438764 Discogs - Diana and the Golden Apples]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/holdingsInfo?searchId=30389&recCount=25&recPointer=0&bibId=14905719|title=Diana and the golden apples|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]}}</ref> An accompanying animated short was also produced by [[Mel-O-Toons]].\n* ''Atalanta and the Arcadian Beast'' is a 2003 novel by [[Robert J. Harris (writer)|Robert J. Harris]] and [[Jane Yolen]], part of the ''Young Heroe'' series.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\">\nFile:Richard Wilson - Meleager and Atalanta - Google Art Project.jpg|Richard Wilson - Meleager and Atalanta (circa 1770)\nFile:Meleager-B\u00e9ierkapp--w.jpg|L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Meleager B\u00e9ierkapp\nFile:Jan Wildens - Landscape with Hunt of Meleager and Atalanta.jpg|Landscape with Hunt of Meleager and Atalanta by Jan Wildens (17th century) at Geschonken aan het museum door Artibus Patriae, Antwerpen, 1938.\nFile:Jacob Jordaens - Meleager en Atalanta.JPG|Meleager and Atalanta by Jacob Jordaens (circa 1618) at the Royal Museum of Fine Arts Antwerp, Belgium\nFile:Meleager presents the Boar's head to Atalanta.jpg|Meleager presents the Boar's head to Atalanta. From Neuer\u00f6ffneter Musen-Tempel by Bernard Picart, 1733 (University of Heidelberg)\nFile:Atalanta and Meleager MET DP261342.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager by Peter Paul Rubens (ca. 1616) at Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York City\nFile:Giulio Romano - Meleager et Atalanta.jpg|\"Meleager et Atalanta\", from a drawing by [[Giulio Romano]], engraved by Fran\u00e7ois Louis Lonsing. Atalanta is the woman on the far left with the bow; Meleager is just right of her, with the boar spear sticking into the Calydonian Boar. (1773)\nFile:Jan Fyt and Pieter Thijs - Atalanta and Meleager Hunt the Calydonian Boar.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager Hunt the Calydonian Boar by Jan Fyt and Pieter Thijs (1648) at Ringling Museum of Art, Sarasota, Florida\nFile:Francesco Mosca, called Il Moschino - Atalanta and Meleager with the Calydonian Boar, ca. 1564-1565 - Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art - DSC08046.JPG|Atalanta and Meleager with the Calydonian Boar by Francesco Mosca, called Il Moschino (ca. 1564-1565).  Exhibit in the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, Kansas City, Missouri\nFile:M. Maurice Stora - Atalanta and Meleager Present the Head of the Caledonian Boar at the Temple of Artemis - Google Art Project.jpg|Atalanta and Meleager Present the Head of the Caledonian Boar at the Temple of Artemis by M. Maurice Stora (1530 - 1535) at Toledo Museum of Art, Toledo, Ohio\nFile:Meleager en Atalanta Rijksmuseum SK-A-4121.jpeg|Meleager en Atalanta (between 1675 and 1699) at Rijksmuseum Amsterdam\nFile:Jacob Jordaens - Meleager and Atalanta, 1620-1650.jpg|Meleager and Atalante by Jacob Jordaens (1620-1650) at Museo Nacional del Prado, Madrid, Spain\nFile:Paolo Veronese (c\u00edrculo) - Atalanta e Hipomenes disputando a corrida.JPG|English:  by Circle of Paolo Veronese (f1550-1600) at National Museum of Ancient Art, Lisbon, Portugal\nFile:No\u00ebl Hall\u00e9 - The Race between Hippomenes and Atalanta - WGA11034.jpg|The Race between Hippomenes and Atalanta by No\u00ebl Hall\u00e9 (1762-1765) at Louvre Museum, Paris\nFile:Herp Atalanta and Hippomenes.jpg|Atalanta and Hippomenes by Willem van Herp (circa 1650) at National Museum in Warsaw\nFile:Les Metamorphoses d'Ovide - Atalanta and Hippomenes.jpg|Engraving by Magdalena van de Passe from book Les Metamorphoses d'Ovide, En Latin Et Fran\u00e7ois: Divis\u00e9es En XV. Livres, page 335. Published 1677.\nFile:Johann Heinrich Sch\u00f6nfeld - Atalanta and Hippomenes - WGA21056.jpg|Atalanta and Hippomenes by Johann Heinrich Sch\u00f6nfeld (1650-1660) at Brukenthal National Museum, Sibiu, Romania\nFile:Francis Derwent Wood, Atalanta Preparing for the Race, front 2, Chelsea Embankment at Albert Bridge, London (3381529189).jpg\nFile:Francis Derwent Wood - Atalanta.jpg\nFile:Atalanta Lepautre Louvre MR1804.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Apollodorus, ''Bibliotheca'' 3. 9. 2 for Atalanta and 1.8.3 for the Boar Hunt\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Atalanta}}\n* [http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/picture-of-month/displaypicture.asp?venue=2&id=6 Rubens's \"Atalanta and Meleager\"] in the [http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/ladylever/ Lady Lever Art Gallery]\n*{{ws|[[s:Landon in The Literary Gazette 1823/Atalanta|Atalanta, represented as a Huntress with her bow]]}} One of the Medallion Wafer poems of [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]] in the Literary Gazette, 1823.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Argonauts]]\n[[Category:Fictional feral children]]\n[[Category:Metamorphoses into animals in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Mythological Greek archers]]\n[[Category:Women in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Princesses in Greek mythology]]\n[[Category:Arcadian mythology]]\n[[Category:Boeotian mythology]]\n[[Category:Family of Athamas]]\n[[Category:Fictional hunters]]\n", "name_user": "Confermusearename", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atalanta"}
